<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>
    <I><B>Note:</B></I> There will be some restructuring until we release the
    next version (There may be some bug fixes, though). It will mainly
    be the <A HREF="telnet.java">telnet.java</A>
    class. It will be divided to make it easier to have the telnet in an
    extra window and we want to clean up some of the button code.<P>
    We also look forward to the new release of the 
    <A HREF="http://www.javasoft.com/products/JDK/1.1/index.html">JDK 
    (version 1.1)</A> which will have
    some enhancements over the current release. Hopefully web browsers will
    support the new JDK soon. Until there is a wide acceptance we will not
    provide classes optimized to the new version.
</H4>
<HR>

<B>The JAVA Telnet Applet</B> is a fully featured telnet applet/application
with embedded <B>VT320/ANSI</B> emulation. It may be used to allow access to
telnet based applications via the web without expecting the user to have his
own telnet application. If you want to test drive it
<A HREF="index.test.html">click here</A>.
<P>

The package contains two parts which divide the functionality into
<A HREF="Documentation/Package-display.html">Display</A> and
<A HREF="Documentation/Package-socket.html">Socket</A> functions. Both may be
used without the telnet itself and are provided to programmers for their own
use. All files have full documentation as
<A HREF="Documentation/AllNames.html">inline java documentation</A>.
<P>

We have added some example applets and applications to either overcome
security restrictons or to show the functionality of the package.
<UL TYPE="SQUARE">
<LI><A HREF="Documentation/appWrapper.html">appWrapper</A> is an
    applet load to be used to allow some independency from web 
    browsers (The <B>\$detach()</B> function will not work properly without 
    <A HREF="Documentation/appWrapper.html">appWrapper</A>!)
    <P>
<LI><A HREF="Documentation/proxy.html">proxy</A> is a simple proxy server for
    telnet (it can be used to redirect connections). Run this little program
    on your web server if your telnet service is located elsewhere!
    <P>
<LI><A HREF="IOtest.java">IOtest.java</A> shows how to use the socket
    package for simple access (works like a script executor).
    <P>
<LI><A HREF="CharDisplay.html">CharDisplayTest</A> shows the abilities of
    the <A HREF="display/CharDisplay.java">display/CharDisplay.java</A> class.
</UL>
<P>

We would really appreciate if users of our applet/application would write us
their impressions (<A HREF="mailto:leo@first.gmd.de">MAILTO LINK</A>) and if
it is used as service please notify us so we can put
your page onto our list of <A HREF="#users">Telnet Applet Users</A>.
<HR>
<A NAME="download">
<H2>Package download and unpacking</H2>
The packages contain all source files as well as compiled .class files, the
full <A HREF="Documentation/AllNames.html">documentation</A>, some test files,
<A HREF="report/">bug reports</A> and <A HREF="INSTALL">installation hints</A>.
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER>
  <TD ALIGN=CENTER><B>UNIX</B></TD> <TD><B>Windows 95/NT</B><TR><P>
  <TD><A HREF="../telnet.tgz">telnet.tgz</A></TD>
  <TD><A HREF="../telnet.zip">telnet.zip (long filenames)!</A></TD>
</TABLE> 
</CENTER>
<DL>
  <DT><B><I>UNIX users:</I></B>
  <DD>The package is tared and gzipped. To unpack it use the following
      command:<BR>
      <B><CODE>gzip -cd telnet.tgz | tar xvf -</CODE></B><BR>
      This will unpack all files into a subdirectory called <B>Telnet/</B>.
      <P>
  <DT><B><I>Windows users:</I></B>
  <DD>The package is zipped with the 1  equivalent of PKzip and contains
      long file names. You will not be able to use the applet if your
      filesystem does not support long file names (Windows 95 VFAT
      does). Unpack the files with the following command in a DOS window:<BR>
      <B><CODE>pkunzip -d telnet.zip</CODE></B><BR>
      You need to give the option <B>-d</B> to force pkunzip to extract the
      subdirectories as well. If you have a Windows program installed that
      unzips .zip packages do not forget to check whether it extracts the
      subdirectories as well!
</DL> 
</A>

